<p>given the following program:</p>  <pre><code>#include &lt;math.h&gt; #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;  int main(void) {     double x = sqrt(2);     printf("The square root of two is %f\n", x);     return 0; } </code></pre>  <p>and compiling with:</p>  <pre><code>gcc calc.c -o calc </code></pre>  <p>succeeds? why doesn't it require -lm or /usr/lib/blah/libm.so.x</p>  <p>inspecting the binary object with ldd produces:</p>  <pre><code>linux-vdso.so.1 (0x00007fff4f5e5000) libc.so.6 =&gt; /lib/x86_64-linux-gnu/libc.so.6 (0x00007feeffd1b000) /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 (0x00007fef000e1000 </code></pre>  <p>No libm is referenced. However, if I look at the libc.so.6 library or the ld-linux-x86-64.so.2 library using nm -D, no sqrt function is in those libraries.</p>  <p>What's going on here? Is gcc magically including a default set of common functions or something else?</p>